<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ920219-0020</DOCNO><DOCID>920219-0020.</DOCID><HL>   Marketing andamp; Media:   Pacific Bell Announces   Three Information Services</HL><DATE>02/19/92</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   PAC</CO><MS>CONSUMER CYCLICAL (CYC)UTILITIES (UTI)</MS><IN>MEDIA, PUBLISHING, BROADCASTING, ELECTRONIC PUBLISHING (MED)PUBLISHING, INFORMATION SERVICES COMPANIES (PUB)REGIONAL TELEPHONE SYSTEMS (RTL)TELEPHONE SYSTEMS, INCLUDING CELLULAR (TLS)</IN><NS>EDUCATION ISSUES (EDU)NEW PRODUCTS andamp; SERVICES (PDT)</NS><RE>CALIFORNIA (CA)NORTH AMERICA (NME)PACIFIC RIM (PRM)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   SAN FRANCISCO -- Pacific Bell announced its first threeinformation services, including a news service to providecustom-tailored reports daily on major stories, sports scoresand stock prices.   The phone company, a unit of Pacific Telesis Group, saidthe services will become widely available next year. Untillast year, all the Baby Bells were barred from offeringinformation services by the 1982 consent decree that broke upthe Bell System.</LP><TEXT>   Along with the news reports, which will be availablethrough the company's voice mail service, Pacific Bell plansto offer an expanded directory assistance service.   The service essentially fills in the blanks for callerswho don't know a company's full name. In addition, the phonecompany could provide a company's hours of operation andaddress complete with nine-digit ZIP code and the crossstreets near the address. The company, however, will needstate regulatory approval before it can offer the service.   Pacific Bell also said it is developing a computerizedinformation service that will give California schools accessto the Internet, a National Science Foundation network, andto information that could help teachers.   The company already offers a &quot;Homework Hotline,&quot; avoice-mail service designed to aid communication betweenschools and parents.</TEXT></DOC>